# Hurricane Andrew

*For other storms of the same name, see [List of storms named Andrew](/List_of_storms_named_Andrew).*

## Category 5 Atlantic hurricane in 1992

What began as a rather unremarkable ripple in the vast, indifferent [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean) in 1992 escalated into [Hurricane Andrew](/Hurricane_Andrew), a compact, yet extraordinarily potent and profoundly destructive [tropical cyclone](/Tropical_cyclone) that carved a path of devastation across [The Bahamas](/The_Bahamas), [Florida](/Florida), and [Louisiana](/Louisiana) that August. It stood, for an uncomfortable period, as the most destructive hurricane to ever inflict itself upon [Florida](/Florida), measured by the sheer volume of structures damaged or utterly obliterated, and held the unenviable title of the costliest in financial terms until [Hurricane Irma](/Hurricane_Irma) decided to surpass it a quarter-century later. Andrew also represented the strongest hurricane to make landfall in the [United States](/United_States) in decades, and, for a time, was the [costliest hurricane](/List_of_costliest_Atlantic_hurricanes) to strike anywhere in the nation, a record it begrudgingly relinquished to the infamously exorbitant [Hurricane Katrina](/Hurricane_Katrina) in 2005.

Andrew is an unwelcome member of an exclusive club: one of only four tropical cyclones known to have made landfall in the continental [United States](/United_States) at the apex of [Category 5](/Category_5_Atlantic_hurricane) intensity. Its predecessors in this grim distinction include the [1935 Labor Day hurricane](/1935_Labor_Day_hurricane), [Hurricane Camille](/Hurricane_Camille) in 1969, and more recently, [Hurricane Michael](/Hurricane_Michael) in 2018. While the storm certainly left its mark of major damage in [The Bahamas](/The_Bahamas) and [Louisiana](/Louisiana), the most profound and concentrated impact was reserved for [South Florida](/South_Florida). There, Andrew made landfall as a true [Category 5 hurricane](/Category_5_Atlantic_hurricane), wielding 1-minute sustained wind speeds that reached an astonishing 165&#160;mph (266&#160;km/h), punctuated by gusts that screamed across the landscape at up to 177&#160;mph (285&#160;km/h).

The hurricane passed directly through what were then the burgeoning cities of [Cutler Bay](/Cutler_Bay,_Florida) and [Homestead](/Homestead,_Florida) within [Dade County](/Miami-Dade_County,_Florida) (now more commonly known as [Miami-Dade County](/Miami-Dade_County,_Florida)). The sheer force of its winds was such that it stripped countless homes of everything but their concrete foundations, leaving behind a scene of catastrophic, almost surgical, destruction. In its wake, Andrew obliterated more than 63,500&#160;houses, inflicted damage upon over 124,000&#160;others, accrued an estimated $27.3&#160;billion in damage (a sum equivalent to approximately $63&#160;billion in 2023, a cost that speaks volumes about the fragility of our meticulously constructed lives), and, with an almost casual brutality, left 65&#160;people dead.

Andrew's genesis was humble, a mere [tropical depression](/Tropical_depression) forming over the eastern [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean) on August&#160;16. After a week of unremarkable existence in the central Atlantic, it decided to shed its anonymity, [rapidly intensifying](/Rapid_intensification) into a formidable [Category 5 hurricane](/Category_5_Atlantic_hurricane) as it tracked relentlessly westward towards [The Bahamas](/The_Bahamas) on August&#160;23. Although Andrew briefly relented, weakening to [Category 4](/Category_4_Atlantic_hurricane) status while traversing [The Bahamas](/The_Bahamas), it quickly reclaimed its [Category 5](/Category_5_Atlantic_hurricane) ferocity before making its Florida landfalls. First, it struck [Elliott Key](/Elliott_Key), then, with a distinct sense of purpose, it slammed into [Homestead](/Homestead,_Florida) on August&#160;24. With a chillingly low barometric pressure of 922&#160;hPa (27.23&#160;inHg) at the moment of its Florida landfall, Andrew etched itself into history as the sixth most-intense hurricane to ever strike the [United States](/United_States). Just hours later, the hurricane re-emerged over the vast expanse of the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico) at a still-potent [Category 4](/Category_4_Atlantic_hurricane) strength, placing the [Gulf Coast of the United States](/Gulf_Coast_of_the_United_States) squarely in its crosshairs. After executing a turn to the northwest and undergoing further, albeit slight, weakening, Andrew moved ashore near [Morgan City, Louisiana](/Morgan_City,_Louisiana), as a low-end [Category 3 storm](/Category_3_Atlantic_hurricane). The now-smaller hurricane curved northeastward following its Louisiana landfall and rapidly dissipated, shedding its tropical characteristics to become an [extratropical cyclone](/Extratropical_cyclone) on August&#160;28. Its atmospheric remnants then merged with those of [Hurricane Lester](/Hurricane_Lester_(1992)) and a lingering [frontal system](/Frontal_system) over the southern [Appalachian Mountains](/Appalachian_Mountains) on August&#160;29, a final, unceremonious end to a truly destructive force.

Andrew's initial display of destructive capability manifested as it tore through [The Bahamas](/The_Bahamas), particularly devastating [Cat Cays](/Cat_Cays), where it lashed the islands with a potent combination of [storm surge](/Storm_surge), [hurricane-force winds](/Hurricane-force_winds), and even localized [tornadoes](/Tornado). Across the archipelago, approximately 800&#160;houses were obliterated, and significant damage was inflicted upon vital infrastructure including transport networks, water and sanitation systems, and the crucial agriculture and fishing sectors. In [The Bahamas](/The_Bahamas), Andrew claimed four lives and left behind an estimated $250&#160;million in damage. In parts of southern [Florida](/Florida), Andrew unleashed truly severe winds; a staggering wind gust of 177&#160;mph (285&#160;km/h) was actually recorded at a house in [Perrine](/Perrine,_Florida) before the instrument gave up the ghost. The cities of [Florida City](/Florida_City,_Florida), [Homestead](/Homestead,_Florida), [Cutler Ridge](/Cutler_Ridge,_Florida), and portions of [Kendall](/Kendall,_Florida) bore the full, brutal brunt of Andrew's fury. At the storm's peak, a staggering 1.4&#160;million people found themselves without power, with some enduring outages for over a month. Within the delicate ecosystem of the [Everglades](/Everglades), a colossal 70,000 acres (280&#160;km 2 ) of trees were downed, and, as a bizarre side effect of human carelessness and natural disaster, invasive [Burmese pythons](/Burmese_python) began their unwelcome [inhabitation of the region](/Burmese_pythons_in_Florida) after a nearby facility housing them was destroyed, a testament to chaos creating new problems. Despite Andrew's rapid forward motion, rainfall in [Florida](/Florida) was substantial in certain localized areas, though notably less in others, peaking at 13.98 inches (355&#160;mm) in western [Dade County](/Miami-Dade_County,_Florida). This uneven distribution led multiple media outlets to label Andrew a "dry hurricane," a rather understated term for such a tempest. In [Florida](/Florida), Andrew was responsible for 44 fatalities and inflicted a then-record $25&#160;billion in damage.

Before its final landfall in [Louisiana](/Louisiana) on August&#160;26, Andrew had already caused extensive damage to [oil platforms in the Gulf of Mexico](/Offshore_oil_and_gas_in_the_Gulf_of_Mexico_(United_States)), leading to a colossal $500&#160;million in losses for the oil industry. Its passage through [Louisiana](/Louisiana) brought [hurricane-force winds](/Hurricane-force_winds) that decimated large swathes of power lines, plunging approximately 230,000&#160;people into darkness. Over 80% of the trees in the vital [Atchafalaya River](/Atchafalaya_River) basin were toppled, and the region's agriculture was utterly devastated. Across both the basin and [Bayou Lafourche](/Bayou_Lafourche), a staggering 187&#160;million freshwater fish perished in the hurricane's turbulent waters. With 23,000&#160;houses damaged, 985&#160;others destroyed, and 1,951&#160;mobile homes reduced to debris, property losses in [Louisiana](/Louisiana) soared past $1.5&#160;billion. The hurricane tragically claimed the lives of 17&#160;people in the state, with 6 of those drowning offshore. Andrew's destructive reach extended further, spawning at least 28&#160;[tornadoes](/Tornado) along the [Gulf Coast](/Gulf_Coast_of_the_United_States), particularly impacting [Alabama](/Alabama), [Georgia](/Georgia_(U.S._state)), and [Mississippi](/Mississippi). In its entirety, Andrew was responsible for 65&#160;deaths and an estimated $27.3&#160;billion in damage. It currently stands as the ninth-costliest [Atlantic hurricane](/Atlantic_hurricane) to impact the [United States](/United_States). Furthermore, by wind speed (165&#160;mph (266&#160;km/h)), it ranks as the third-strongest hurricane to strike the U.S. mainland. The sheer scale of destruction and loss of life caused by the storm led the [World Meteorological Organization](/World_Meteorological_Organization) to officially retire the name Andrew in the spring of 1993, consigning it to the annals of meteorological infamy, never to be reused for another [Atlantic hurricane](/Atlantic_hurricane).

## Meteorological history

