On August 14, a fairly typical [tropical wave](/Tropical_wave) began its eastward journey off the west coast of [Africa](/Africa). Driven by a persistent [ridge](/Ridge_(meteorology)) of high pressure situated to its north, this wave progressed rapidly westward, almost as if it had an appointment with destiny. An area of concentrated [convection](/Convection)—essentially, enthusiastic thunderstorm activity—began to coalesce along the wave axis, just south of the [Cape Verde](/Cape_Verde) islands. By August 15, ever-vigilant [meteorologists](/Meteorologist) initiated the process of classifying this nascent system using the [Dvorak technique](/Dvorak_technique), a method for estimating intensity based on satellite imagery. The thunderstorms grew more organized, and distinct, narrow spiral [rainbands](/Rainband) began to emerge, wrapping themselves around a nascent [center of circulation](/Atmospheric_circulation). It is estimated that what would become [Tropical Depression Three](/Tropical_Depression_Three_(1992)) officially formed late on August 16, roughly 1,630&#160;mi (2,620&#160;km) east-southeast of the serene island of [Barbados](/Barbados). Embedded within the deep easterlies, a common atmospheric highway for tropical systems, the depression tracked west-northwestward at a brisk 20&#160;mph (32&#160;km/h). Initially, the presence of moderate [wind shear](/Wind_shear)—a disruptive force of varying wind speeds and directions at different atmospheric levels—acted as a natural inhibitor, preventing any significant strengthening. However, a timely decrease in this shear allowed the depression to finally gather itself, intensifying into a tropical storm. The [National Hurricane Center](/National_Hurricane_Center) (NHC) officially bestowed the name Andrew upon it at 12:00&#160;[UTC](/UTC) on August 17.

By the morning of August 18, Andrew had managed to maintain its central convection, with spiral bands gracefully extending to its west, all while its winds steadily increased to a respectable 50&#160;mph (80&#160;km/h). But, like many things in life, this progress was fleeting. Shortly thereafter, the storm began to lose its forward momentum and its internal cohesion, a consequence of increased southwesterly [wind shear](/Wind_shear) emanating from an [upper-level low](/Upper-level_low) pressure system. On August 19, a reconnaissance flight by brave [hurricane hunters](/Hurricane_hunters) into the storm failed to locate anything resembling a well-defined center, suggesting a disheveled, unorganized mess. The following day, another flight found that the cyclone had degenerated further, leaving only a diffuse low-level circulation center. Observations from this period indicated that the [barometric pressure](/Barometric_pressure) had risen to an unusually high 1,015&#160;mbar (29.97&#160;inHg), a clear sign of weakening. Yet, paradoxically, the flight also revealed that Andrew maintained a surprisingly vigorous circulation aloft, hinting at latent power. It seems even storms have their secrets.

The tide began to turn when the disruptive [upper-level low](/Upper-level_low) weakened and fractured into a [trough](/Trough_(meteorology)), effectively reducing the inhibiting [wind shear](/Wind_shear) over the storm. Simultaneously, a robust high-pressure system developed over the southeastern [United States](/United_States), extending its influence eastward and compelling Andrew to execute a sharp turn to the west. This atmospheric realignment proved to be Andrew's turning point. Convection within the storm became more organized, and the upper-level [outflow](/Outflow_(meteorology))—the exhaust system of a hurricane—became better established, allowing the storm to breathe and strengthen. An ominous [eye](/Eye_(cyclone)) began to form, a clear indicator of a powerful, mature system. Andrew officially attained hurricane status early on August 22, now positioned approximately 650&#160;mi (1,050&#160;km) east-southeast of [Nassau, Bahamas](/Nassau,_Bahamas). In the forecast issued just six hours after its upgrade to a hurricane, the cyclone was predicted to make [landfall](/Landfall) near [Jupiter, Florida](/Jupiter,_Florida), with winds of 105&#160;mph (169&#160;km/h) on August 25. A rather significant underestimation, as it turned out, of both the storm's ultimate ferocity and its speed, a miscalculation that would prove costly for [South Florida](/South_Florida).

Hurricane Andrew at peak intensity while approaching [Eleuthera](/Eleuthera) on August 23

The hurricane, now a coiled spring, accelerated westward, plunging into an environment of exceptionally favorable atmospheric conditions. It began to [rapidly intensify](/Rapid_intensification) late on August 22, a terrifying display of nature's raw power. The atmospheric pressure within its core plummeted by a staggering 47&#160;mbar (1.388&#160;inHg), reaching a chilling minimum of 922&#160;mbar (27.23&#160;inHg) within a mere 24‑hour period. On August 23, the storm ascended to the apex of the [Saffir–Simpson scale](/Saffir%E2%80%93Simpson_scale), achieving [maximum sustained winds](/Maximum_sustained_wind) of 175&#160;mph (282&#160;km/h) just a short distance off [Eleuthera](/Eleuthera) in [the Bahamas](/The_Bahamas) at 18:00 UTC. What made Andrew particularly insidious was its relatively small stature despite its immense power, a compact, destructive force. Its tropical storm-force winds, those capable of significant damage, extended out only about 90&#160;mi (140&#160;km) from its center, making it a highly concentrated threat. After reaching this peak intensity, the hurricane underwent an [eyewall replacement cycle](/Eyewall_replacement_cycle), a natural process where a new, larger eyewall forms around the original, often causing a temporary weakening before re-strengthening.

At 21:00 UTC on August 23, Andrew made its first significant landfall, striking [Eleuthera](/Eleuthera) as a [Category 5 hurricane](/Category_5_Atlantic_hurricanes), with winds still raging at 160&#160;mph (260&#160;km/h). The cyclone did weaken somewhat while traversing the shallow [Bahama Banks](/Bahama_Banks), and at 01:00 UTC on August 24, Andrew impacted the southern [Berry Islands](/Berry_Islands) of [The Bahamas](/The_Bahamas) as a [Category 4 hurricane](/Category_4_Atlantic_hurricanes), with winds of 150&#160;mph (240&#160;km/h). However, its brief respite was over. As it moved over the exceptionally warm waters of the [Gulf Stream](/Gulf_Stream), the hurricane rapidly re-intensified, its eye shrinking in size and its eyewall convection deepening, a clear signal of renewed vigor. At 08:40 UTC on August 24, Andrew delivered its devastating blow to [Elliott Key](/Elliott_Key) as a [Category 5 hurricane](/Category_5_Atlantic_hurricanes), with winds of 165&#160;mph (266&#160;km/h) and a pressure of 926&#160;mbar (27.34&#160;inHg). Just about 25&#160;minutes after this initial Florida landfall, Andrew made another, even more significant, landfall just northeast of [Homestead, Florida](/Homestead,_Florida), with a slightly lower, and thus more intense, pressure of 922&#160;mbar (27.23&#160;inHg). This barometric pressure cemented Andrew's place as the most intense hurricane to strike the [United States](/United_States) since [Hurricane Camille](/Hurricane_Camille) in the [1969 Atlantic hurricane season](/1969_Atlantic_hurricane_season), and the strongest tropical cyclone to make landfall in [Florida](/Florida) since the infamous [Labor Day hurricane](/1935_Labor_Day_hurricane) of [1935 Atlantic hurricane season](/1935_Atlantic_hurricane_season). The [United States](/United_States) would not witness another landfall from a hurricane at [Category 5](/Category_5_Atlantic_hurricanes) intensity until the arrival of [Hurricane Michael](/Hurricane_Michael) in the [2018 Atlantic hurricane season](/2018_Atlantic_hurricane_season), a testament to Andrew's rare and extreme power.

