As the eye of Andrew moved onshore in [Florida](/Florida), the convection within its eyewall actually strengthened further, a counterintuitive effect due to increased atmospheric convergence. [Hurricane Hunters](/Hurricane_hunters) reported a warmer eyewall temperature than two hours prior, indicating a temporary surge of internal energy. However, Andrew inevitably began to weaken as it pushed further inland, battling the friction of land. After traversing southern [Florida](/Florida) in a grueling four hours, the storm emerged into the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico) with winds still formidable at 130&#160;mph (210&#160;km/h). Over the warm waters of the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico), the eye remained remarkably well-defined as the hurricane executed a turn to the west-northwest, a change in trajectory attributed to the weakening of the high-pressure [ridge](/Ridge_(meteorology)) that had been steering it. Andrew steadily re-intensified over the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico), reaching winds of 145&#160;mph (233&#160;km/h) late on August 25. As the high-pressure system to its north continued to wane, a strong mid-latitude [trough](/Trough_(meteorology)) began to approach the area from the northwest. This atmospheric interaction caused the hurricane to decelerate as it lumbered northwestward, and its winds began to decrease as Andrew drew closer to the [Gulf Coast of the United States](/Gulf_Coast_of_the_United_States).

At 08:30 UTC on August 26, the cyclone made its final significant landfall, approximately 20&#160;mi (32&#160;km) west-southwest of [Morgan City, Louisiana](/Morgan_City,_Louisiana), with winds of 115&#160;mph (185&#160;km/h). Andrew then weakened with remarkable rapidity as it veered to the north and northeast, devolving into tropical storm intensity within a mere 10 hours. Upon entering [Mississippi](/Mississippi), the cyclone further weakened into a [tropical depression](/Tropical_depression) early on August 27. Accelerating northeastward, the depression began the process of merging with the approaching [frontal system](/Weather_front), and by midday on August 28, Andrew had shed its tropical characteristics entirely, transforming into an [extratropical cyclone](/Extratropical_cyclone) while situated over the southern [Appalachian Mountains](/Appalachian_Mountains). The remnants of the storm, like a ghost still moving, continued their northeastward trajectory, finally merging fully with the remnants of [Hurricane Lester](/Hurricane_Lester_(1992)) and a lingering frontal zone over [Pennsylvania](/Pennsylvania) on August 29, effectively erasing Andrew from the meteorological map.

Post-analysis of Andrew's journey revealed that the storm was, in fact, often stronger than initially reported in real-time between early on August 22 and early on August 26. Operationally, the [National Hurricane Center](/National_Hurricane_Center) (NHC) had assessed its peak intensity as 150&#160;mph (240&#160;km/h). This was later upgraded to 155&#160;mph (249&#160;km/h) in a more thorough post-storm analysis conducted after the hurricane season concluded. However, a comprehensive 2004 paper by [Christopher Landsea](/Christopher_Landsea) and his colleagues definitively concluded that Andrew had indeed achieved [Category 5 hurricane](/List_of_Category_5_Atlantic_hurricanes) status near [The Bahamas](/The_Bahamas) on August 23, reaching truly maximum sustained winds of 175&#160;mph (282&#160;km/h). The paper further indicated that Andrew briefly re-intensified back to a [Category 5 hurricane](/List_of_Category_5_Atlantic_hurricanes) around the time of its devastating landfall in [South Florida](/South_Florida) early on August 24. While approaching [Louisiana](/Louisiana), the storm was found to have been slightly more potent than initially assessed, but its landfall winds were subsequently adjusted downward from 120 to 115&#160;mph (193 to 185&#160;km/h). Details, you see, always matter.

## Preparations

### Bahamas

At 1500&#160;[UTC](/Coordinated_Universal_Time) on August&#160;22, a full 30&#160;hours before Andrew made its destructive entrance, the government of [The Bahamas](/The_Bahamas) issued a [hurricane watch](/Hurricane_watch) for the entirety of the [northwest Bahamas](/Districts_of_the_Bahamas). This included the islands of [Andros](/Andros,_Bahamas) and [Eleuthera](/Eleuthera), extending northward through [Grand Bahama](/Grand_Bahama) and [Great Abaco](/Andros,_Bahamas). Just six hours later, this watch was prudently upgraded to a full-fledged [hurricane warning](/Tropical_cyclone_warnings_and_watches), and approximately 15&#160;hours prior to landfall, a hurricane warning was further extended to the central Bahamas, encompassing [Cat Island](/Cat_Island_(Bahamas)), [Exuma](/Exuma), [San Salvador Island](/San_Salvador_Island), and [Long Island](/Long_Island,_Bahamas). All watches and warnings were, of course, discontinued on August 24 once Andrew had passed. This significant advance warning, a rare luxury in the unpredictable dance with nature, was widely credited for the remarkably low death toll in the country. A total of 58&#160;shelters, hastily established in churches, government buildings, and schools, were opened to the public.

[Prime Minister](/Prime_Minister_of_the_Bahamas) of [The Bahamas](/The_Bahamas), [Hubert Ingraham](/Hubert_Ingraham), who had the unenviable timing of taking office while the storm was actively brewing, issued a stern and urgent plea to residents: "take this hurricane seriously." Before the hurricane's relentless passage through [The Bahamas](/The_Bahamas), forecasters had predicted a [storm surge](/Storm_surge) that could reach an alarming 18&#160;ft (5.5&#160;m), accompanied by up to 8&#160;in (200&#160;mm) of torrential rain.

In a subsequent, rather candid, analysis by Arthur Rolle, the Bahamas Chief Meteorological Officer, national emergency agencies, including the venerable [Red Cross](/International_Red_Cross_and_Red_Crescent_Movement) and the [Royal Bahamas Defence Force](/Royal_Bahamas_Defence_Force), were praised for having "responded exceptionally well to the hurricane alerts." However, the same report also pointed out, with a hint of exasperation, that the public "[exhibited] a degree of complacency, particularly in [New Providence](/New_Providence) and The Current, [Eleuthera](/Eleuthera)." Ultimately, despite this human tendency towards dismissal, the advance warning of the hurricane proved instrumental in mitigating the loss of life from the storm. The hurricane, with its impeccable sense of timing, struck just four days after [Hubert Ingraham](/Hubert_Ingraham) assumed the role of Bahamian Prime Minister, marking the first change in leadership in 25&#160;years. There was initial concern, naturally, over how Ingraham would navigate this immediate crisis, especially with many government officials remaining from the previous administration; however, the government's response to the hurricane was, by all accounts, surprisingly normal and effective.

### Florida

•
Main article: [Effects of Hurricane Andrew in Florida](/Effects_of_Hurricane_Andrew_in_Florida)

Hurricane Andrew shortly after landfall near [Homestead](/Homestead,_Florida)

Initially, forecasters, perhaps still underestimating Andrew's true potential, predicted tides that could reach up to 14&#160;ft (4.3&#160;m) above normal along the east coast of [Florida](/Florida), specifically near the projected location of landfall. Rainfall was modestly projected to be between 5 and 8&#160;in (130 and 200&#160;mm) along the storm's path. Furthermore, the [National Hurricane Center](/National_Hurricane_Center) (NHC) noted the distinct likelihood of isolated [tornadoes](/Tornado) manifesting in Central and [South Florida](/South_Florida) during Andrew's passage on August 23 and 24, an additional layer of chaotic destruction. Several tropical storm and hurricane warnings were swiftly issued for much of Central and [South Florida](/South_Florida), stretching from [Titusville](/Titusville,_Florida) on the east coast all the way to [Venice](/Venice,_Florida) on the west coast. These warnings ominously included [Lake Okeechobee](/Lake_Okeechobee) and the entirety of the [Florida Keys](/Florida_Keys). By 18:00 UTC on August 24, all watches and warnings were, with a sigh of relief, discontinued after Andrew had made its unwelcome exit into the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico).

[Governor](/Governor_of_Florida) [Lawton Chiles](/Lawton_Chiles) wasted no time declaring a [state of emergency](/State_of_emergency) and activated approximately one-third of the [Florida National Guard](/Florida_National_Guard), a prudent measure given the impending disaster. A significant exodus of residents ensued, most evacuating voluntarily, from [Broward](/Broward_County,_Florida), [Charlotte](/Charlotte_County,_Florida), [Collier](/Collier_County,_Florida), [Lee](/Lee_County,_Florida), [Martin](/Martin_County,_Florida), [Dade](/Miami-Dade_County,_Florida), [Monroe](/Monroe_County,_Florida), [Palm Beach](/Palm_Beach_County,_Florida), and [Sarasota](/Sarasota_County,_Florida) counties. A total of 142&#160;shelters were hastily opened across these counties, collectively providing refuge for at least 84,340&#160;people, a testament to the sheer scale of the threat. In [Dade County](/Miami-Dade_County,_Florida) alone, a staggering 515,670&#160;people were issued mandatory evacuation orders. As Andrew bore down, an estimated 20,000–30,000&#160;tourists found themselves in the precarious position of being in the [Florida Keys](/Florida_Keys) ([Monroe County](/Monroe_County,_Florida)). Overall, nearly 1.2&#160;million people evacuated, a monumental logistical undertaking that undoubtedly contributed to the mercifully low number of fatalities, despite the storm's extreme intensity. Many evacuees also flooded hotels, with rooms completely booked as far north as [Ocala](/Ocala,_Florida). This mass movement ultimately led to what was likely the largest traffic jam in [Florida](/Florida)'s history, primarily clogging [Interstate 95](/Interstate_95_in_Florida), a less-than-ideal prelude to a hurricane. [United States Coast Guard](/United_States_Coast_Guard) vessels located on or near the [Florida](/Florida) coastline were either secured onshore or dispatched to ride out the storm's fury at sea, a risky but sometimes necessary maneuver. Government offices, along with public and private schools, were shuttered from [Monroe County](/Monroe_County,_Florida) northward to [St. Lucie County](/St._Lucie_County,_Florida). Numerous colleges and universities in southeast [Florida](/Florida) also ceased operations. Major airports, including [Fort Lauderdale–Hollywood](/Fort_Lauderdale%E2%80%93Hollywood_International_Airport), [Key West](/Key_West_International_Airport), [Miami](/Miami_International_Airport), and [Palm Beach](/Palm_Beach_International_Airport) international airports, were all closed, effectively isolating the region from the outside world.

### Gulf Coast of the United States

Satellite image of Hurricane Andrew approaching [Louisiana](/Louisiana) on August 25

Shortly after the storm, like a malevolent entity, emerged into the [Gulf of Mexico](/Gulf_of_Mexico) from southern [Florida](/Florida), the [National Hurricane Center](/National_Hurricane_Center) (NHC) wasted no time issuing hurricane watches and warnings for the [Gulf Coast of the United States](/Gulf_Coast_of_the_United_States), commencing at 13:00 UTC on August 24. Following the initial hurricane watch, which stretched from [Mobile, Alabama](/Mobile,_Alabama), to [Sabine Pass, Texas](/Sabine_Pass,_Port_Arthur,_Texas), these watches and warnings were progressively expanded to eventually encompass areas from [Mobile, Alabama](/Mobile,_Alabama), to [Freeport, Texas](/Freeport,_Texas). All watches and warnings along the [Gulf Coast](/Gulf_Coast_of_the_United_States) were finally discontinued late on August 26, after the hurricane had moved inland over [Louisiana](/Louisiana) and begun its final, weakened march.

In response to the looming hurricane threat, workers swiftly evacuated [oil platforms in the Gulf of Mexico](/Offshore_oil_and_gas_in_the_Gulf_of_Mexico_(United_States)), while the ever-present [Coast Guard](/United_States_Coast_Guard) diligently moved their boats inland to safety. Officials in [Mississippi](/Mississippi) sagely suggested that approximately 100,000&#160;people evacuate the vulnerable [coastal counties](/List_of_counties_in_Mississippi). Shelters were opened in [Hancock](/Hancock_County,_Mississippi) and [Harrison](/Harrison_County,_Mississippi) counties, though, perhaps reflecting that peculiar human tendency towards denial, only 68&#160;people sought refuge in the former. [Gambling ships](/Riverboat_casino), those temples of chance, were prudently moved into harbors and inland canals. Two run-offs for special [legislative](/Mississippi_Legislature) elections, inconveniently scheduled for August 25, were, quite rightly, postponed.

In [Louisiana](/Louisiana), [Governor](/Governor_of_Louisiana) [Edwin Edwards](/Edwin_Edwards) wasted no time in declaring a state of emergency, a grim formality for what was to come. Approximately 1.25&#160;million people evacuated from central and southeast [Louisiana](/Louisiana), a truly massive undertaking, while an additional 60,000&#160;others fled [parishes](/List_of_parishes_in_Louisiana) in southwest [Louisiana](/Louisiana). A mandatory evacuation order for [Grand Isle](/Grand_Isle,_Louisiana) was issued by Mayor Andy Valence and the city council, leaving no room for debate. In [New Orleans](/New_Orleans), Mayor [Sidney Barthelemy](/Sidney_Barthelemy) took decisive action, ordering the evacuation of roughly 200,000&#160;residents residing in the city's low-lying, vulnerable areas. Nine shelters were quickly established in the city, providing refuge for thousands of anxious people. In a direct response to ominous computer simulations that suggested a [storm surge](/Storm_surge) from a tropical cyclone like Andrew could potentially over-top [the levees](/Drainage_in_New_Orleans), workers swiftly closed 111&#160;[floodgates](/Floodgate), a crucial defensive measure. The [New Orleans International Airport](/Louis_Armstrong_New_Orleans_International_Airport) was shut down, with its massive jumbo jets prudently flown to other, safer airports. A total of 250&#160;members of the [Louisiana National Guard](/Louisiana_National_Guard) were deployed to patrol the streets during the storm, maintaining order in the face of chaos. The [American Red Cross](/American_Red_Cross) played its part, assisting in the opening of a shelter at the [University of Southwest Louisiana](/University_of_Southwest_Louisiana)'s [Cajundome](/Cajundome) in [Lafayette](/Lafayette,_Louisiana), a facility equipped to handle about 2,000&#160;people.

In [Texas](/Texas), approximately 250,000&#160;people evacuated [Orange](/Orange_County,_Texas) and [Jefferson](/Jefferson_County,_Texas) counties, demonstrating a healthy respect for the storm's potential. [Galveston](/Galveston,_Texas) City Manager Doug Matthews, with admirable foresight, advised residents to formulate an evacuation plan, just in case the city itself decided to call for evacuations, a decision they later opted against. School was, quite sensibly, canceled on August 25 for [Beaumont](/Beaumont,_Texas), [Port Arthur](/Port_Arthur,_Texas), and other areas of central [Jefferson County](/Jefferson_County,_Texas), while further closures impacted schools in [Dickinson](/Dickinson,_Texas), [High Island](/High_Island,_Texas), [Hitchcock](/Hitchcock,_Texas), [La Marque](/La_Marque,_Texas), [Santa Fe](/Santa_Fe,_Texas), and [Texas City](/Texas_City,_Texas) on August 26. Educational institutions like [College of the Mainland](/College_of_the_Mainland), [Galveston College](/Galveston_College), and [Texas A&M University at Galveston](/Texas_A%26M_University_at_Galveston) also closed their doors. Emergency management crews in [Corpus Christi](/Corpus_Christi,_Texas) began the practical work of testing emergency generators and severe weather gear, ensuring readiness. The [Comal County](/Comal_County,_Texas) chapter of the [American Red Cross](/American_Red_Cross) placed their disaster alert teams on standby, poised to respond should the hurricane decide to threaten the [Corpus Christi metropolitan area](/Corpus_Christi_metropolitan_area).

